PEOPLE v. DWYER. No. 9555; July 28, 1884. 4 Pac. 451. Intoxicating Liquor—Authority of Board of Supervisors.—Judgment reversed and cause remanded, on the authority of Ex parte Walters, 3 Pac. 894, holding that boards of supervisors have power to regulate the sale of spirituous liquors within their counties by imposing a license on the sale of such liquors at retail.1 APPEAL from the Superior Court of Sacramento County. The facts in this case are the same as in Ex parte Walters, 3 Pae. 894.

Henry Edgerton and Matt. F. Johnson for appellant; A. L. Rhodes, E. J. Pringle and Milton E. Babb for respondent.

Cited and approved in In re Guerrero, 69 Cal. 94, 10 Pac. 266, holding that boards of supervisors may regulate the sale of liquors by imposing licenses upon retailers.

 By the COURT.

On the authority of Ex parte Walters, 3 Pac. 894, judgment reversed and cause remanded.
